{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:47:15.828869+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's a summary of how to run, build, and preview this React admin app locally and for different environments, based on the repository contents.\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThis is a **Vite + React + TypeScript + MUI** admin app (project name: `vite-react-ts-admin`). It uses **yarn** as its package manager and **cross-env** for environment switching.\n\n---\n\n## Running Locally (Development)\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Node.js (LTS recommended)\n- Yarn\n\n### One-time setup (via [Taskfile](Taskfile.yaml))\n```bash\ntask init\n```\nThis will:\n1. Install global tools (`conventional-changelog-cli`, `standard-version`, `commitizen`)\n2. Copy the local env file into the project root: `cp envs/.env.local .env`\n3. Install dependencies: `yarn install`\n\nAlternatively, do it manually:\n```bash\ncp envs/.env.local .env\nyarn install\nyarn dev\n```\n\n### Dev server details\n- **Command:** `yarn dev` → runs `cross-env NODE_ENV=local vite --host`\n- **Port:** `10086` (configured in `envs/.env.local` as `VITE_PORT`)\n- **Host binding:** `--host` flag makes it accessible on your local network\n- **API base URL:** `https://mock.local.lantron.ltd`\n\n### Staging dev mode\n```bash\nyarn dev:stg\n```\nUses `envs/.env.stg` (port `10086`, API: `https://mock.stg.lantron.ltd`).\n\n---\n\n## Environment Files\n\nThe `envs/` directory holds three environment configurations:\n\n| File | NODE_ENV | VITE_PORT | VITE_APP_BASE_API |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `.env.local` | `local` | `10086` | `https://mock.local.lantron.ltd` |\n| `.env.stg` | `stg` | `10086` | `https://mock.stg.lantron.ltd` |\n| `.env.prod` | `prod` | (empty) | `https://mock.lantron.ltd` |\n\nThe Vite config (`vite.config.ts`) loads the correct `.env` file by checking for a root `.env` first, then falling back to `envs/.env.<NODE_ENV>`.\n\n---\n\n## Building for Production / Staging\n\n### Production build\n```bash\nyarn build:prod\n```\nRuns `vite build --mode production`. Output goes to the `dist/` directory.\n\n### Staging build\n```bash\nyarn build:stg\n```\nRuns `vite build --mode test`.\n\n### Generic build\n```bash\nyarn build\n```\nRuns `vite build --mode prod`.\n\n---\n\n## Previewing a Build Locally\n\nAfter building, preview the static output with:\n```bash\nyarn serve\n```\nThis runs `vite preview --host`, serving the contents of `dist/` for local testing.\n\n---\n\n## Deployment Options\n\n### 1. GitHub Pages\n```bash\nyarn deploy\n```\nUses `gh-pages -d dist` to publish the `dist/` folder to GitHub Pages.\n\n### 2. Docker (Nginx)\n```bash\ndocker build -t vite-react-admin .\ndocker run -p 80:80 vite-react-admin\n```\nThe `Dockerfile` performs a multi-stage build:\n- **Stage 1:** Builds the app with `yarn && yarn build`\n- **Stage 2:** Serves the built assets via **Nginx** on port 80, using `nginx.conf` with SPA fallback (`try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html`)\n\n### 3. Netlify\nA `netlify.toml` is included with a catch-all redirect rule (`/* → /`, status 200) for SPA routing. Just connect the repo to Netlify and set the build command to `yarn build:prod`.\n\n---\n\n## Linting & Formatting\n\n```bash\nyarn lint      # Check for ESLint issues\nyarn fix       # Auto-fix ESLint issues\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Copy the right `.env` from `envs/` to the project root, `yarn install`, then `yarn dev` to develop locally. Use `yarn build:prod` / `yarn build:stg` for environment-specific builds, `yarn serve` to preview, and deploy via Docker, GitHub Pages, or Netlify.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 996, "prompt_tokens": 12563, "total_tokens": 13559, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 12, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 11712, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_toke